{"title_page": "Little Things (Jeannie Seely album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Little Things\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| cover      = Jeannie Seely--Little Things.jpg\n| released   = {{start date|1968|12}}\n| recorded   = August 1967 \u2013 August 1968\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{hlist|Bradley's Barn|Fred Foster Sound Studio}}\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web |title=''Little Things'' -- Jeannie Seely: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/little-things-mw0001028574 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Monument Records]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Fred Foster]]|[[Jim Malloy (recording engineer)|Jim Malloy]]}}\n| prev_title = [[I'll Love You More]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = Jeannie Seely\n| next_year  = 1969\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Little Things\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Welcome Home to Nothing\n | single1date = January 1968\n | single2     = How Is He\n | single2date = May 1968\n | single3     = Little Things\n | single3date = September 1968\n }}\n}}\n'''''Little Things''''' is a studio album by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]]. It was released in December 1968 on [[Monument Records]] and was co-produced by [[Fred Foster]] and [[Jim Malloy (recording engineer)|Jim Malloy]]. The record was Seely's fourth studio album recorded and released. It spawned three singles in 1968. Two of these singles became hits on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country chart. The album would be Seely's final studio release while recording for Monument.\n\n==Background and content==\n''Little Things'' was recorded in several sessions between August 1967 and August 1968. Some of the musical sessions were recorded at the Fred Foster Sound Studio while the remaining cuts were recorded at Bradley's Barn. Both venues were located in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. Most of the album's sessions were produced by [[Fred Foster]], Seely's longtime collaborator at Monument. However, four tracks were produced by [[Jim Malloy (recording engineer)|Jim Malloy]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Little Things'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=December 1968}}</ref> The album contained 11 tracks. One of these tracks, \"Maybe I Should Leave\", was penned by Seely herself. Three of the tracks were written by Seely's then-husband and songwriter, [[Hank Cochran]]. The title track was composed by [[Willie Nelson]] and his wife [[Shirley Collie|Shirley Nelson]].<ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- ''Little Things'' (1968, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Little-Things/release/5004021 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The album also included cover versions of songs previously recorded by other music artists. Among these tracks was \"[[Harper Valley PTA]]\", previously recorded by [[Jeannie C. Riley]] the same year. The seventh track, \"[[Dreams of the Everyday Housewife]]\", was first cut by [[Glen Campbell]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Little Things'' was released in December 1968 on Monument Records. It was originally issued as a [[gramophone record|vinyl record]], with five songs of the first side and six songs on the opposite side of the record.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> In the 2010s, the project was released in a digital format.<ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite web |title=''Little Things'' by Jeannie Seely |url=https://music.apple.com/no/album/little-things/1438897996?l=nb |website=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> ''Little Things'' peaked at number 36 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart in January 1969. It became Seely's fourth album to place on the list.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Little Things'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/831937 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The project also included three singles released by Seely in 1968. The three singles issued from the album failed to become major hits, instead reaching top 40 positions on the ''Billboard'' country singles chart. The first single, \"Welcome Home to Nothing\", reached number 24 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart in April 1968.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Welcome Home to Nothing\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/837256 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The next single issued, \"How Is He\", peaked at number 23 on the same chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"How Is He\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/835115 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The third single spawned from the album was the title track, which did not chart on any ''Billboard'' publication.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\nThe album received reviews since its release. A 1968 review by ''Billboard'' gave the record a positive reception. \"Jeannie Seely only needs the right tune to score hard; she has several tunes here in that category,\" writers commented.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Billboard Album Reviews |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 28, 1968 |volume=80 |issue=52}}</ref> In later years, the album was reviewed by [[Allmusic]] and it received a rating of 2.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n===Original edition===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one<ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n| title1          = Little Things\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Shirley Collie|Shirley Nelson]]|[[Willie Nelson]]}}\n| length1         = 3:29\n| title2          = Just Because I'm a Woman\n| writer2         = [[Dolly Parton]]\n| length2         = 2:12\n| title3          = Maybe I Should Leave\n| writer3         = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| length3         = 2:20\n| title4          = Welcome Home to Nothing\n| writer4         = [[Hank Cochran]]\n| length4         = 2:38\n| title5          = A Little Unfair\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Cochran|Chuck Howard}}\n| length5         = 2:32\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side two<ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n| title1          = Leave Me Alone\n| writer1         = Cochran\n| length1         = 2:38\n| title2          = [[Dreams of the Everyday Housewife]]\n| writer2         = [[Chris Gantry]]\n| length2         = 2:52\n| title3          = How Is He\n| writer3         = [[Marijohn Wilkin]]\n| length3         = 2:00\n| title4          = [[Harper Valley PTA]]\n| writer4         = [[Tom T. Hall]]\n| length4         = 3:14\n| title5          = My Love Dies Hard\n| writer5         = [[Ed Bruce]]\n| length5         = 2:42\n| title6          = Long Black Limousine \n| writer6         = {{hlist|Bobby George|Vern Stovall}}\n| length6         = 3:50\n}}\n\n===Digital edition===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Digital edition<ref name=\"Apple\"/>\n| title1          = Little Things\n| writer1         = {{hlist|S. Nelson|W. Nelson}}\n| length1         = 3:29\n| title2          = Just Because I'm a Woman\n| writer2         = Parton\n| length2         = 2:12\n| title3          = Maybe I Should Leave\n| writer3         = Seely\n| length3         = 2:20\n| title4          = Welcome Home to Nothing\n| writer4         = Cochran\n| length4         = 2:38\n| title5          = A Little Unfair\n| writer5         = {{hlist|Cochran|Howard}}\n| length5         = 2:32\n| title6          = Leave Me Alone\n| writer6         = Cochran\n| length6         = 2:38\n| title7          = Dreams of the Everyday Housewife\n| writer7         = Gantry\n| length7         = 2:52\n| title8          = How Is He\n| writer8         = Wilkin\n| length8         = 2:00\n| title9          = Harper Valley PTA\n| writer9         = Hall\n| length9         = 3:14\n| title10          = My Love Dies Hard\n| writer10         = Bruce\n| length10         = 2:42\n| title11          = Long Black Limousine \n| writer11         = {{hlist|George|Stovall}}\n| length11         = 3:50\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nAll credits are adapted from the [[liner notes]] of ''Little Things''.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n* Hank Cochran \u2013 liner notes\n* [[Fred Foster]] \u2013 [[record producer|producer]]\n* Ken Kim \u2013 photography\n* [[Jim Malloy (recording engineer)|Jim Malloy]] \u2013 producer \n* Cam Mullins \u2013 arrangement\n* Jeannie Seely \u2013 lead vocals\n* Tommy Strong \u2013 engineering\n* Charlie Tallent \u2013 engineering\n* Mort Thomasson \u2013 engineering\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1969)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCountry|36|artist=Jeannie Seely|rowheader=true|date=20200121|accessdate=April 5, 2020}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Region\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Format\n!scope=\"col\"| Label\n!scope=\"col\"| Ref.\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United States\n| February 1968\n| Vinyl\n| [[Monument Records|Monument]]\n| <ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n|-\n| November 23, 2018\n| Music download\n| [[Sony Music Entertainment]]\n| <ref name=\"Apple\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n[[Category:1968 albums]]\n[[Category:Jeannie Seely albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Fred Foster]]\n[[Category:Monument Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Little Things\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| cover      = Jeannie Seely--Little Things.jpg\n| released   = {{start date|1968|12}}\n| recorded   = August 1967 \u2013 August 1968\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{hlist|Bradley's Barn|Fred Foster Sound Studio}}\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web |title=''Little Things'' -- Jeannie Seely: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/little-things-mw0001028574 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Monument Records]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Fred Foster]]|[[Jim Malloy (recording engineer)|Jim Malloy]]}}\n| prev_title = [[I'll Love You More]]\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = Jeannie Seely\n| next_year  = 1969\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Little Things\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Welcome Home to Nothing\n | single1date = January 1968\n | single2     = How Is He\n | single2date = May 1968\n | single3     = Little Things\n | single3date = September 1968\n }}\n}}\n'''''Little Things''''' is a studio album by American [[country music|country]] artist [[Jeannie Seely]]. It was released in December 1968 on [[Monument Records]] and was co-produced by [[Fred Foster]] and [[Jim Malloy]]. The record was Seely's fourth studio album recorded and released. It spawned three singles in 1968. Two of these singles became hits on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country chart. The album would be Seely's final studio release while recording for Monument.\n\n==Background and content==\n''Little Things'' was recorded in several sessions between August 1967 and August 1968. Some of the musical sessions were recorded at the Fred Foster Sound Studio while the remaining cuts were recorded at Bradley's Barn. Both venues were located in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. Most of the album's sessions were produced by [[Fred Foster]], Seely's longtime collaborator at Monument. However, four tracks were produced by [[Jim Malloy (recording engineer)|Jim Malloy]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Little Things'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=December 1968}}</ref> The album contained 11 tracks. One of these tracks, \"Maybe I Should Leave\", was penned by Seely herself. Three of the tracks were written by Seely's then-husband and songwriter, [[Hank Cochran]]. The title track was composed by [[Willie Nelson]] and his wife [[Shirley Collie|Shirley Nelson]].<ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- ''Little Things'' (1968, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jeannie-Seely-Little-Things/release/5004021 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The album also included cover versions of songs previously recorded by other music artists. Among these tracks was \"[[Harper Valley PTA]]\", previously recorded by [[Jeannie C. Riley]] the same year. The seventh track, \"[[Dreams of the Everyday Housewife]]\", was first cut by [[Glen Campbell]].<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''Little Things'' was released in December 1968 on Monument Records. It was originally issued as a [[gramophone record|vinyl record]], with five songs of the first side and six songs on the opposite side of the record.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\"/> In the 2010s, the project was released in a digital format.<ref name=\"Apple\">{{cite web |title=''Little Things'' by Jeannie Seely |url=https://music.apple.com/no/album/little-things/1438897996?l=nb |website=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> ''Little Things'' peaked at number 36 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Top Country Albums]] chart in January 1969. It became Seely's fourth album to place on the list.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Little Things'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/831937 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The project also included three singles released by Seely in 1968. The three singles issued from the album failed to become major hits, instead reaching top 40 positions on the ''Billboard'' country singles chart. The first single, \"Welcome Home to Nothing\", reached number 24 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart in April 1968.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Welcome Home to Nothing\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/837256 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The next single issued, \"How Is He\", peaked at number 23 on the same chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"How Is He\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/835115 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The third single spawned from the album was the title track, which did not chart on any ''Billboard'' publication.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref>\n\nThe album received reviews since its release. A 1968 review by ''Billboard'' gave the record a positive reception. \"Jeannie Seely only needs the right tune to score hard; she has several tunes here in that category,\" writers commented.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Billboard Album Reviews |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 28, 1968 |volume=80 |issue=52}}</ref> In later years, the album was reviewed by [[Allmusic]] and it received a rating of 2.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n===Original edition===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Side one<ref name=\"Discogs\"/>\n| title1          = Little Things\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Shirley Collie|Shirley Nelson]]|[[Willie Nelson]]}}\n| length1         = 3:29\n| title2          = Just Because I'm a Woman\n| writer2         = [[Dolly Parton]]\n| length2         = 2:12\n| title3          = Maybe I Should Leave\n| writer3         = [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| length3         = 2:20\n| title4  